### Function to Convert Markdown to HTML  
Converts a given Markdown string to its corresponding HTML representation.  

**Function Signature**:  
```cpp
std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown);
```

**Explanation**:  
1. **Input**: A reference to a `std::string` containing Markdown text.  
2. **Output**: A `std::string` containing the corresponding HTML text.  
3. **Implementation**:  
   - Use a regular expression to match Markdown syntax and replace it with HTML equivalents.  
   - Handle common Markdown elements like headers, lists, links, and images.  
   - Return the resulting HTML string.  

**Example Usage**:  
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Replace Markdown syntax with HTML equivalents
    std::string html = regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("#(\\s+)?(.+)"), "<h$1>$2</h$1>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("##(\\s+)?(.+)"), "<h2$1>$2</h2$1>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("###(\\s+)?(.+)"), "<h3$1>$2</h3$1>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("####(\\s+)?(.+)"), "<h4$1>$2</h4$1>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("#####(\\s+)?(.+)"), "<h5$1>$2</h5$1>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("######(\\s+)?(.+)"), "<h6$1>$2</h6$1>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("^(\\s*)-(\\s*)\\w+\\s+(.*)$"), "<li>$3</li>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("^\\s*\\*\\s+(.*)$"), "<li>$1</li>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("^\\s*\\d+\\.\\s+(.*)$"), "<li>$1</li>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("\\[(\\w+)\\]\\((\\S+)\\)"), "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");
    html = regex_replace(html, std::regex("!\\[(\\w+)\\]\\((\\S+)\\)"), "<img src=\"$2\" alt=\"$1\">");
    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "## Heading\n\n- Item 1\n- Item 2\n\n[Link](https://example.com)\n\n![Image](https://example.com/image.png)";
    std::string html = convertMarkdownToHTML(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

